ip nums[4],nums[5],nums[6]: nums becomes [1,1,1,1,1,0,0,0]\nFlip nums[5],nums[6],nums[7]: nums becomes [1,1,1,1,1,1,1,1]\n\n \nConstraints:\n\n1 <= nums.length <= 105\n1 <= k <= nums.length\n\n\n\n### Format: You will use the following starter code to write the solution to the problem and enclose your code within delimiters.\n```python\nclass Solution:\n    def minKBitFlips(self, nums: List[int], k: int) -> int:\n        \n```\n\n### Answer: (use the provided format with backticks)\n", "response": "```python\nfrom typing import List\n\nclass Solution:\n    def minKBitFlips(self, nums: List[int], k: int) -> int:\n        n = len(nums)\n        flip_count = 0\n        flip_status = [0] * (n + 1)  # To keep track of the flip operations\n        flip_times = 0  # To keep track of the number of flips at the current position\n\n        for i in range(n):\n            # Update the flip_times based on the flip_status\n            flip_times += flip_status[i]\n            \n            # If the current bit is 0 and flip_times is even, or if the current bit is 1 and flip_times is odd, we need to flip\n            if (nums[i] == 0 and flip_times % 2 == 0) or (nums[i] == 1 and flip_times % 2 == 1):\n                # If flipping is not possible (not enough elements left to form a subarray of length k)\n                if i + k > n:\n                    return -1\n                # Mark the end of the flip operation\n                flip_status[i + k] -= 1\n                # Increment the flip_times\n                flip_times += 1\n                # Increment the flip_count\n                flip_count += 1\n\n        return flip_count\n```\n\n### Explanation:\n- We use a `flip_status` array to keep track of the end of flip operations. This helps us efficiently determine if a position needs to be flipped.\n- `flip_times` keeps track of the cumulative number of flips that affect the current position.\n- We iterate through the array `nums`, and for each position, we check if it needs to be flipped based on the current `flip_times`.\n- If a flip is needed and there are not enough elements left to form a subarray of length `k`, we return `-1`.\n- Otherwise, we perform the flip by updating `flip_status` and incrementing `flip_times` and `flip_count`.\n- Finally, we return the total number of flips performed.", "estimated_date": 1550361600000}